user.biography:
Documentary Storyteller • People • Wildlife
Based in Dubai with my husband and two girls, posting stories about my life at home and on the road.

node.text:
My heart is back at the beach. But my head feels halfway between excited for what’s to come and nervous that nothing has happened yet. I hate waiting on others to make things happen and I’m SO impatient. So many exciting things are just over the horizon, buying a flat 🤞🏼, my (potential) first work trip, my first shoot (booked!)... it’s all on its way and I’m excited and nervous and feeling all the feelings. Anxious to be working as hard is I was before Rumi but anxious to make sure she has the best of me whenever she needs it. I’m nervous about how it’ll all shake out but I’m excited to make it work. I’ve always made it work in the past and I know I will again ✨

node.text: A little something I created for Visit Wales last year.
I've been working on editing a film about a kids club in Kenya and I stumbled on this! Caught in the act by @jeremysnell

My first film on Instagram! It's part of a project I spent a lot of last year working on across across a few different countries. All the footage was shot by @jeremysnell and I edited it together as a part of a larger branding project for @thebrookecharity.
I'll be producing a similar project again this year and they're a lot of work but I can't wait to get started!

node.text: A coal miner settles into prayer at the end of a long day spent underground in the mines. A moment of freedom in an otherwise cramped and oppressive daily life. I could only manage a few hours at a time underground, bent double in 40+ degree heat, only carrying the weight of my camera. And as I type this no doubt this man will be deep into a mine, starting another days work, a routine he will continue for years.

node.text:
Today this beautiful girl turns three ✨
Becoming a mama cracked me open in the most beautiful and uncomfortable way. From the moment she was born I could feel myself stretching and changing - there’s no way I could be who I am today without this beautiful light in my life. I’m grateful for her every moment, especially the difficult ones where she reminds me that I have a choice in how I want to show up for her and for myself.
Rumi is such a dreamer, always in her own world, so kind, so independent, and so so funny. She brings so much love to those around her and every moment is an adventure. She cannot wait for baby sister to arrive - she has already picked out a name for her!!! (it was one from our list, actually the only one Adam and I can agree on, I’m just not sure what will happen if we decide to go for a different name because she flat out refuses to take any other suggestions!😬)
Also, I’ve been waiting for a special moment to photograph these dresses - a gift from @shopdoen. These are without a doubt the most beautiful outfits we own and will be pieces we will treasure forever - after baby sister has her turn the dress Rumi is wearing it will be carefully wrapped up and put away for generations to come, it’s THAT beautiful ✨ All their clothes are - sustainable, ethical, and just so beautiful 💛

I don’t know where I’d be without her ✨ I’m grateful for this girl of mine every day and the way she continues to crack my heart right open without even trying.
Even when she makes me talk to her in the character of a blue toothbrush sherif with a southern drawl ALL DAY, and then 30 seconds later it’s an alien that pronounces every word beginning with the letter Q. And sometimes I have to combine the two… 🤯

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Freya Dowson ☼ Photographer on June 28, 2021. May be an image of nature.

node.text:
Sometimes I think it’s important to publicly out my biggest fears and admit to the thoughts that keep me up at night. We all make up stories about our lives but the more I live in a story like this, the more it becomes my reality and the harder it is to get out of bed in the morning.

I never post stuff like this for sympathy or for someone to tell me why it’s not true, in fact sympathy makes it so much worse and other people opinions bounce right off these kind of thoughts. And I do picture the face of everyone I know reading this and it makes me cringe. But mostly I post it for myself, and maybe someone else who reads it and thinks “me too, thank goodness I’m not the only one”. I have no desire to come across as negative… better days will come, and then go and then come back again. But here’s where my head has been lately… off and on for the past three or more (probably much more) years...

Some mornings I wake up and my shadow is in bed next to me, telling me everything awful and negative about myself. It follows me around for days, reminding me of everything I am most ashamed of: that I haven’t worked properly (the kind of work I love) since Rumi was born, my career is irrelevant, I’m irrelevant, my photos are old and outdated now - so am I.

Continued in comments…
